%% The abstract is a short summary of the work to be presented in the
%% article.
\begin{abstract}
  This paper presents research into the design of a Domain-Specific Language (DSL) capable of compiling to both high-quality \LaTeX\ documents with formal mathematical notation and Haskell libraries, automating the process of creating text and code representations of algorithms.
  To validate the design, a prototype implementation of the designed DSL is showcased that enables expressing algorithms in the field of Computational Number Theory.
  Additionally, the tool supports the automatic embedding of runtime evaluation results into the document output, promoting reproducible science.
  Future work can focus on expanding this concept beyond the syntax required for these algorithms, covering a larger area of mathematics.
\end{abstract}

